post_text:
“I wasn’t sure if my child was able to attend the best charter school.”

“Everybody tells a different story about how to enroll their child.”

“One person says it’s based on who you know, and another says it’s based on where you live.”

In Indiana public schools, as long as there is an available seat, attendance is based solely on a first-come, first-served basis...

...not on race, income, or neighborhood.

All students deserve the same chance to develop their talents and excel.

Your child’s education is just as important to us as any other.

Find a truly equal enrollment opportunity at Paramount Schools of Excellence.

post_text:
My friends felt like their children lost four months of learning last spring.

Their school just couldn’t figure out the transition to Virtual Learning.

With their kids in chaos, working from home was impossible for them.

Our children were right on track and continued advancing with Virtual Learning.

They had a structured school day with everything planned and in one place.

Teachers were responsive and the whole staff was supportive and available.

Since I’m also working from home, I can’t stop and fuss over their lessons.

Paramount Schools of Excellence is ready for virtual pathways or on-campus instruction - parents have the option.

“One-step-ahead” is our usual pace at Paramount Schools of Excellence.

post_text:
Dear Paramount Families,
Based on Mayor Hogsett's announcement delaying schools starting, Paramount will be delaying the start of the school year by one week. All Paramount schools will be opening both in-school and virtually on August 10th. Should new regulations from the Mayor or Marion County Public Health Department require the start date to shift even further, we will contact you with the new guidance. Please expect orientation communication such as welcome calls and back to school orientation Zoom meetings to occur as previously scheduled. Should you have any questions, please reach out to your school's front office.
text:
Dear Paramount Families,
Based on Mayor Hogsett's announcement delaying schools starting, Paramount will be delaying the start of the school year by one week. All Paramount schools will be opening both in-school and virtually on August 10th. Should new regulations from the Mayor or Marion County Public Health Department require the start date to shift even further, we will contact you with the new guidance. Please expect orientation communication such as welcome calls and back to school orientation Zoom meetings to occur as previously scheduled. Should you have any questions, please reach out to your school's front office.

text: Three weeks of eLearning completed! You've got this. A huge thanks to all our students, families, and staff whose hard work is making it happen.

post_text:
Governor Holcomb announced that Indiana schools would remain closed for the rest of the school year. This announcement does not affect eLearning at Paramount Schools of Excellence. Our schools will continue to provide students and families the highest quality of education and support through April and early May.

Because of our commitment to our school community, PSOE schools didn't stop our eLearning for spring break. This decision allowed us to keep our momentum, making sure our students were engaged. It also meant continued meal service, resulting in the delivery of thousands of servings to our families. Because we chose not to take this break, we are adjusting the end of our school year by four days. Paramount's school year will come to an end one week earlier on Friday, May 15, 2020.

post_text: Your feedback on how Paramount's E-Learning Plan is working for your family is appreciated. We are committed to providing the academic and social supports our students and families need during this challenging time. A big part of our E-Learning services is being available to answer your questions, connect you to resources or assist with technology. School call centers are open M-F from 8:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m.
shared_text:
Arial Burrus is at Paramount Schools of Excellence.
March 17 at 8:59 AM · Indianapolis, IN ·

I want to applaud Paramount Schools of Excellence for how well they prepared our children for the possibility of being out of school. Everything was so well organized and instructions very easy to follow. Students were allowed to take home their chrome books if they had internet access and if they didn’t, the teachers created an organized binder with all of the students work. The daily schedule is easy to follow and teachers are available via email, text, or phone if help is needed. Additionally, the school offers breakfast and lunch everyday for students who may not have daily access to a meal otherwise.

Very well done Paramount!

post_text:
PSOE Families,

At the recommendation of the Indianapolis Mayor's Office, all Paramount Schools will be closing for two weeks beginning on Monday, March 16th. We "will" be in session tomorrow, Friday, March 13th for a full day of instruction with normal hours. Our expected return date is Monday, April 6th. Please note that Paramount Schools of Excellence are taking the mandate from the city on closure, and we DO NOT have a case of COVID-19 within our school community.

Beginning Monday, all Paramount Schools will begin utilizing our e-learning platform. On Monday morning, your child's teacher will be reaching out by phone to walk you through the e-Learning process. We look forward to seeing our students for one final day of instruction tomorrow.

post_text:
Paramount Proud x 2!

We are excited to announce that Paramount Brookside has received two coveted academic recognitions. For the 5th consecutive year, the school has achieved the state’s A-rating and the U.S. Secretary of Education has designated Paramount as a 2018 National Blue Ribbon School. The acknowledgments are a result of the school’s consistent academic performance over the last eight years.

Congratulations to our Paramount students, staff and families for all your hard work.

post_text: It was a busy weekend for Paramount. Butler University's @Ambassadors of Change 2018 students spent a morning helping out on the Paramount Farm. Saturday, Indy Moca unveiled the Holy Cross Neighborhood mural that is located at Indy Downtown Doggie. The mural was a collaboration with Paramount’s 8th grade students who played a pivotal role in the mural’s design and painting.
